# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: infrared-spectroscopy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The term *Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy* originates from the fact that a Fourier transform (a mathematical process) is required to convert the raw data into the actual spectrum.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Absorption spectroscopy techniques (e.g., FTIR, ultraviolet-visible ("UV-vis") spectroscopy) measure how much light a sample absorbs at each wavelength.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The most straightforward way to do this, the "dispersive spectroscopy" technique, is to shine a monochromatic light beam at a sample, measure how much of the light is absorbed, and repeat for each different wavelength.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The dispersive spectroscopy technique is used by some UV–vis spectrometers to take measurements.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Fourier transform spectroscopy is a less intuitive way to obtain the same information.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Rather than shining a monochromatic beam of light (a beam composed of only a single wavelength) at the sample, this technique shines a beam containing many frequencies of light at once and measures how much of that beam is absorbed by the sample.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Next, the beam is modified to contain a different combination of frequencies, giving a second data point.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] This process is rapidly repeated many times over a short time span.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Afterwards, a computer takes all this data and works backward to infer what the absorption is at each wavelength.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The beam described above is generated by starting with a broadband light source—one containing the full spectrum of wavelengths to be measured.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The light shines into a Michelson interferometer—a certain configuration of mirrors, one of which is moved by a motor.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] As this mirror moves, each wavelength of light in the beam is periodically blocked, transmitted, blocked, transmitted, by the interferometer, due to wave interference.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Different wavelengths are modulated at different rates, so that at each moment or mirror position the beam coming out of the interferometer has a different spectrum.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] As mentioned, computer processing is required to turn the raw data (light absorption for each mirror position) into the desired result (light absorption for each wavelength).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The processing required turns out to be a common algorithm called the Fourier transform.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The Fourier transform converts one domain (in this case displacement of the mirror in cm) into its inverse domain (wavenumbers in cm−1).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The raw data is called an "interferogram".
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The first low-cost spectrophotometer capable of recording an infrared spectrum was the Perkin-Elmer Infracord produced in 1957.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] This instrument covered the wavelength range from 2.5 μm to 15 μm (wavenumber range 4,000 cm−1 to 660 cm−1).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The lower wavelength limit was chosen to encompass the highest known vibration frequency due to a fundamental molecular vibration.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The upper limit was imposed by the fact that the dispersing element was a prism made from a single crystal of rock-salt (sodium chloride), which becomes opaque at wavelengths longer than about 15 μm; this spectral region became known as the rock-salt region.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Later instruments used potassium bromide prisms to extend the range to 25 μm (400 cm−1) and caesium iodide 50 μm (200 cm−1).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The region beyond 50 μm (200 cm−1) became known as the far-infrared region; at very long wavelengths it merges into the microwave region.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Measurements in the far infrared needed the development of accurately ruled diffraction gratings to replace the prisms as dispersing elements, since salt crystals are opaque in this region.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] More sensitive detectors than the bolometer were required because of the low energy of the radiation.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] An additional issue is the need to exclude atmospheric water vapour because water vapour has an intense pure rotational spectrum in this region.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Far-infrared spectrophotometers were cumbersome, slow and expensive.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The advantages of the Michelson interferometer were well-known, but considerable technical difficulties had to be overcome before a commercial instrument could be built.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Also an electronic computer was needed to perform the required Fourier transform, and this only became practicable with the advent of minicomputers, such as the PDP-8, which became available in 1965.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Digilab pioneered the world's first commercial FTIR spectrometer (Model FTS-14) in 1969.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Digilab FTIRs are now a part of Agilent Technologies's molecular product line after Agilent acquired spectroscopy business from Varian.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] In a Michelson interferometer adapted for FTIR, light from the polychromatic infrared source, approximately a black-body radiator, is collimated and directed to a beam splitter.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Ideally 50% of the light is refracted towards the fixed mirror and 50% is transmitted towards the moving mirror.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Light is reflected from the two mirrors back to the beam splitter and some fraction of the original light passes into the sample compartment.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] There, the light is focused on the sample.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] On leaving the sample compartment the light is refocused on to the detector.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The difference in optical path length between the two arms to the interferometer is known as the *retardation* or *optical path difference* (OPD).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] An interferogram is obtained by varying the OPD and recording the signal from the detector for various values of the OPD.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The form of the interferogram when no sample is present depends on factors such as the variation of source intensity and splitter efficiency with wavelength.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] This results in a maximum at zero OPD, when there is constructive interference at all wavelengths, followed by series of "wiggles".
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The position of zero OPD is determined accurately by finding the point of maximum intensity in the interferogram.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] When a sample is present the background interferogram is modulated by the presence of absorption bands in the sample.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Commercial spectrometers use Michelson interferometers with a variety of scanning mechanisms to generate the path difference.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Common to all these arrangements is the need to ensure that the two beams recombine exactly as the system scans.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The simplest systems have a plane mirror that moves linearly to vary the path of one beam.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] In this arrangement the moving mirror must not tilt or wobble as this would affect how the beams overlap as they recombine.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Some systems incorporate a compensating mechanism that automatically adjusts the orientation of one mirror to maintain the alignment.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Arrangements that avoid this problem include using cube corner reflectors instead of plane mirrors as these have the property of returning any incident beam in a parallel direction regardless of orientation.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Systems where the path difference is generated by a rotary movement have proved very successful.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] One common system incorporates a pair of parallel mirrors in one beam that can be rotated to vary the path without displacing the returning beam.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Another is the double pendulum design where the path in one arm of the interferometer increases as the path in the other decreases.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] A quite different approach involves moving a wedge of an IR-transparent material such as KBr into one of the beams.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Increasing the thickness of KBr in the beam increases the optical path because the refractive index is higher than that of air.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] One limitation of this approach is that the variation of refractive index over the wavelength range limits the accuracy of the wavelength calibration.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The interferogram has to be measured from zero path difference to a maximum length that depends on the resolution required.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] In practice the scan can be on either side of zero resulting in a double-sided interferogram.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Mechanical design limitations may mean that for the highest resolution the scan runs to the maximum OPD on one side of zero only.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The interferogram is converted to a spectrum by Fourier transformation.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] This requires it to be stored in digital form as a series of values at equal intervals of the path difference between the two beams.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] To measure the path difference a laser beam is sent through the interferometer, generating a sinusoidal signal where the separation between successive maxima is equal to the wavelength of the laser (typically a 633 nm HeNe laser is used).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] This can trigger an analog-to-digital converter to measure the IR signal each time the laser signal passes through zero.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Alternatively, the laser and IR signals can be measured synchronously at smaller intervals with the IR signal at points corresponding to the laser signal zero crossing being determined by interpolation.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] This approach allows the use of analog-to-digital converters that are more accurate and precise than converters that can be triggered, resulting in lower noise.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The result of Fourier transformation is a spectrum of the signal at a series of discrete wavelengths.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The range of wavelengths that can be used in the calculation is limited by the separation of the data points in the interferogram.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The shortest wavelength that can be recognized is twice the separation between these data points.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] For example, with one point per wavelength of a HeNe reference laser at 0.633 μm (15800 cm−1) the shortest wavelength would be 1.266 μm (7900 cm−1).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Because of aliasing, any energy at shorter wavelengths would be interpreted as coming from longer wavelengths and so has to be minimized optically or electronically.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The spectral resolution, i.e. the separation between wavelengths that can be distinguished, is determined by the maximum OPD.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The wavelengths used in calculating the Fourier transform are such that an exact number of wavelengths fit into the length of the interferogram from zero to the maximum OPD as this makes their contributions orthogonal.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] This results in a spectrum with points separated by equal frequency intervals.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] For a maximum path difference d adjacent wavelengths λ1 and λ2 will have n and (n+1) cycles, respectively, in the interferogram.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The separation is the inverse of the maximum OPD.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] For example, a maximum OPD of 2 cm results in a separation of 0.5 cm−1.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] This is the spectral resolution in the sense that the value at one point is independent of the values at adjacent points.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Most instruments can be operated at different resolutions by choosing different OPD's.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Instruments for routine analyses typically have a best resolution of around 0.5 cm−1, while spectrometers have been built with resolutions as high as 0.001 cm−1, corresponding to a maximum OPD of 10 m.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The point in the interferogram corresponding to zero path difference has to be identified, commonly by assuming it is where the maximum signal occurs.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] This so-called centerburst is not always symmetrical in real world spectrometers so a phase correction may have to be calculated.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The interferogram signal decays as the path difference increases, the rate of decay being inversely related to the width of features in the spectrum.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] If the OPD is not large enough to allow the interferogram signal to decay to a negligible level there will be unwanted oscillations or sidelobes associated with the features in the resulting spectrum.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] To reduce these sidelobes the interferogram is usually multiplied by a function that approaches zero at the maximum OPD.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] This so-called apodization reduces the amplitude of any sidelobes and also the noise level at the expense of some reduction in resolution.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] For rapid calculation the number of points in the interferogram has to equal a power of two.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] A string of zeroes may be added to the measured interferogram to achieve this.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] More zeroes may be added in a process called zero filling to improve the appearance of the final spectrum although there is no improvement in resolution.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Alternatively, interpolation after the Fourier transform gives a similar result.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] There are three principal advantages for an FT spectrometer compared to a scanning (dispersive) spectrometer.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The throughput or Jacquinot's advantage (named after Pierre Jacquinot).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] This results from the fact that in a dispersive instrument, the monochromator has entrance and exit slits which restrict the amount of light that passes through it.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The interferometer throughput is determined only by the diameter of the collimated beam coming from the source.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Although no slits are needed, FTIR spectrometers do require an aperture to restrict the convergence of the collimated beam in the interferometer.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] This is because convergent rays are modulated at different frequencies as the path difference is varied.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Such an aperture is called a Jacquinot stop.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] For a given resolution and wavelength this circular aperture allows more light through than a slit, resulting in a higher signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The wavelength accuracy or Connes's advantage (named after Janine Connes).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The wavelength scale is calibrated by a laser beam of known wavelength that passes through the interferometer.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] This is much more stable and accurate than in dispersive instruments where the scale depends on the mechanical movement of diffraction gratings.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] In practice, the accuracy is limited by the divergence of the beam in the interferometer which depends on the resolution.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Another minor advantage is less sensitivity to stray light, that is radiation of one wavelength appearing at another wavelength in the spectrum.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] In dispersive instruments, this is the result of imperfections in the diffraction gratings and accidental reflections.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] In FT instruments there is no direct equivalent as the apparent wavelength is determined by the modulation frequency in the interferometer.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The interferogram belongs in the length dimension.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Fourier transform (FT) inverts the dimension, so the FT of the interferogram belongs in the reciprocal length dimension([L−1]), that is the dimension of wavenumber.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The spectral resolution in cm−1 is equal to the reciprocal of the maximal OPD in cm.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Thus a 4 cm−1 resolution will be obtained if the maximal OPD is 0.25 cm; this is typical of the cheaper FTIR instruments.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Much higher resolution can be obtained by increasing the maximal OPD.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] This is not easy, as the moving mirror must travel in a near-perfect straight line.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The use of corner-cube mirrors in place of the flat mirrors is helpful, as an outgoing ray from a corner-cube mirror is parallel to the incoming ray, regardless of the orientation of the mirror about axes perpendicular to the axis of the light beam.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] A spectrometer with 0.001 cm−1 resolution is now available commercially.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The throughput advantage is important for high-resolution FTIR, as the monochromator in a dispersive instrument with the same resolution would have very narrow entrance and exit slits.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] In 1966 Janine Connes measured the temperature of the atmosphere of Venus by recording the vibration-rotation spectrum of Venusian CO2 at 0.1 cm−1 resolution.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] FTIR is a method of measuring infrared absorption and emission spectra.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] For a discussion of *why* people measure infrared absorption and emission spectra, i.e. why and how substances absorb and emit infrared light, see the article: Infrared spectroscopy.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] FTIR spectrometers are mostly used for measurements in the mid and near IR regions.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] For the mid-IR region, 2−25 μm (5,000–400 cm−1), the most common source is a silicon carbide (SiC) element heated to about 1,200 K (930 °C; 1,700 °F) (Globar).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Shorter wavelengths of the near-IR, 1−2.5 μm (10,000–4,000 cm−1), require a higher temperature source, typically a tungsten-halogen lamp.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The long wavelength output of these is limited to about 5 μm (2,000 cm−1) by the absorption of the quartz envelope.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] For the far-IR, especially at wavelengths beyond 50 μm (200 cm−1) a mercury discharge lamp gives higher output than a thermal source.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Far-IR spectrometers commonly use pyroelectric detectors that respond to changes in temperature as the intensity of IR radiation falling on them varies.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The sensitive elements in these detectors are either deuterated triglycine sulfate (DTGS) or lithium tantalate (LiTaO3).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] These detectors operate at ambient temperatures and provide adequate sensitivity for most routine applications.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] To achieve the best sensitivity the time for a scan is typically a few seconds.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Cooled photoelectric detectors are employed for situations requiring higher sensitivity or faster response.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Liquid nitrogen cooled mercury cadmium telluride (MCT) detectors are the most widely used in the mid-IR.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] With these detectors an interferogram can be measured in as little as 10 milliseconds.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Uncooled indium gallium arsenide photodiodes or DTGS are the usual choices in near-IR systems.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Very sensitive liquid-helium-cooled silicon or germanium bolometers are used in the far-IR where both sources and beamsplitters are inefficient.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] An ideal beam-splitter transmits and reflects 50% of the incident radiation.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] However, as any material has a limited range of optical transmittance, several beam-splitters may be used interchangeably to cover a wide spectral range.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] In a simple Michelson interferometer, one beam passes twice through the beamsplitter but the other passes through only once.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] To correct for this, an additional compensator plate of equal thickness is incorporated.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] For the mid-IR region, the beamsplitter is usually made of KBr with a germanium-based coating that makes it semi-reflective.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] KBr absorbs strongly at wavelengths beyond 25 μm (400 cm−1), so CsI or KRS-5 are sometimes used to extend the range to about 50 μm (200 cm−1).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] ZnSe is an alternative where moisture vapour can be a problem, but is limited to about 20 μm (500 cm−1).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] CaF2 is the usual material for the near-IR, being both harder and less sensitive to moisture than KBr, but cannot be used beyond about 8 μm (1,200 cm−1).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Far-IR beamsplitters are mostly based on polymer films, and cover a limited wavelength range.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Attenuated total reflectance (ATR) is one accessory of FTIR spectrophotometer to measure surface properties of solid or thin film samples rather than their bulk properties.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Generally, ATR has a penetration depth of around 1 or 2 micrometers depending on sample conditions.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The interferogram in practice consists of a set of intensities measured for discrete values of OPD.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The difference between successive OPD values is constant.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Thus, a discrete Fourier transform is needed.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The fast Fourier transform (FFT) algorithm is used.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The first FTIR spectrometers were developed for far-infrared range.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The reason for this has to do with the mechanical tolerance needed for good optical performance, which is related to the wavelength of the light being used.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] For the relatively long wavelengths of the far infrared, ~10 μm tolerances are adequate, whereas for the rock-salt region tolerances have to be better than 1 μm.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] A typical instrument was the cube interferometer developed at the NPL and marketed by Grubb Parsons.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] It used a stepper motor to drive the moving mirror, recording the detector response after each step was completed.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] With the advent of cheap microcomputers it became possible to have a computer dedicated to controlling the spectrometer, collecting the data, doing the Fourier transform and presenting the spectrum.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] This provided the impetus for the development of FTIR spectrometers for the rock-salt region.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The problems of manufacturing ultra-high precision optical and mechanical components had to be solved.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] A wide range of instruments are now available commercially.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Although instrument design has become more sophisticated, the basic principles remain the same.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Nowadays, the moving mirror of the interferometer moves at a constant velocity, and sampling of the interferogram is triggered by finding zero-crossings in the fringes of a secondary interferometer lit by a helium–neon laser.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] In modern FTIR systems the constant mirror velocity is not strictly required, as long as the laser fringes and the original interferogram are recorded simultaneously with higher sampling rate and then re-interpolated on a constant grid, as pioneered by James W.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] This confers very high wavenumber accuracy on the resulting infrared spectrum and avoids wavenumber calibration errors.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The near-infrared region spans the wavelength range between the rock-salt region and the start of the visible region at about 750 nm.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Overtones of fundamental vibrations can be observed in this region.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] It is used mainly in industrial applications such as process control and chemical imaging.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] FTIR can be used in all applications where a dispersive spectrometer was used in the past (see external links).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] In addition, the improved sensitivity and speed have opened up new areas of application.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Spectra can be measured in situations where very little energy reaches the detector.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy is used in geology, chemistry, materials, botany and biology research fields.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] FTIR spectroscopy is often used in geology to quantify volatile species, H2O and CO2, in minerals, glasses, and melt inclusions.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Quantifying the concentrations of these volatiles is important, as these volatiles influence magma storage conditions, crystallization, degassing, and eruption style — all of which modulate the properties of magmas such as density and viscosity.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] In silicate glasses and melt inclusions, absorbance bands in the near- and mid-IR associated with H2O (dissolved in melts as OH- or H2O2) and CO2 (dissolved in melts as CO32- or CO2) can be quantified into concentrations with the Beer-Lambert Law.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] In nominally anhydrous minerals, trace amounts of H+ are measured to understand mantle water storage and other magmatic processes.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] FTIR is also used to investigate various nanomaterials and proteins in hydrophobic membrane environments.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Studies show the ability of FTIR to directly determine the polarity at a given site along the backbone of a transmembrane protein.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The bond features involved with various organic and inorganic nanomaterials and their quantitative analysis can be done with the help of FTIR.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] An infrared microscope allows samples to be observed and spectra measured from regions as small as 5 microns across.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Images can be generated by combining a microscope with linear or 2-D array detectors.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The spatial resolution can approach 5 microns with tens of thousands of pixels.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The images contain a spectrum for each pixel and can be viewed as maps showing the intensity at any wavelength or combination of wavelengths.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] This allows the distribution of different chemical species within the sample to be seen.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] This technique has been applied in various biological applications including the analysis of tissue sections as an alternative to conventional histopathology, examining the homogeneity of pharmaceutical tablets, and for differentiating morphologically-similar pollen grains.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The spatial resolution of FTIR can be further improved below the micrometer scale by integrating it into scanning near-field optical microscopy platform.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The corresponding technique is called nano-FTIR and allows for performing broadband spectroscopy on materials in ultra-small quantities (single viruses and protein complexes) and with 10 to 20 nm spatial resolution.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The speed of FTIR allows spectra to be obtained from compounds as they are separated by a gas chromatograph.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] However this technique is little used compared to GC-MS (gas chromatography-mass spectrometry) which is more sensitive.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] The GC-IR method is particularly useful for identifying isomers, which by their nature have identical masses.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Liquid chromatography fractions are more difficult because of the solvent present.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] One notable exception is to measure chain branching as a function of molecular size in polyethylene using gel permeation chromatography, which is possible using chlorinated solvents that have no absorption in the area in question.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Measuring the gas evolved as a material is heated allows qualitative identification of the species to complement the purely quantitative information provided by measuring the weight loss.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] FTIR analysis is used to determine water content in fairly thin plastic and composite parts, more commonly in the laboratory setting.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] Such FTIR methods have long been used for plastics, and became extended for composite materials in 2018, when the method was introduced by Krauklis, Gagani and Echtermeyer.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/fourier-transform-infrared-spectroscopy] FTIR method uses the maxima of the absorbance band at about 5200 cm−1, which correlates with the true water content in the material.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The infrared portion of the electromagnetic spectrum is usually divided into three regions; the near-, mid- and far- infrared, named for their relation to the visible spectrum.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The higher-energy near-IR, approximately 14,000–4,000 cm−1 (0.7–2.5 μm wavelength) can excite overtone or combination modes of molecular vibrations.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The mid-infrared, approximately 4,000–400 cm−1 (2.5–25 μm) is generally used to study the fundamental vibrations and associated rotational–vibrational structure.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The far-infrared, approximately 400–10 cm−1 (25–1,000 μm) has low energy and may be used for rotational spectroscopy and low frequency vibrations.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The region from 2–130 cm−1, bordering the microwave region, is considered the terahertz region and may probe intermolecular vibrations.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The names and classifications of these subregions are conventions, and are only loosely based on the relative molecular or electromagnetic properties.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Infrared spectroscopy is a simple and reliable technique widely used in both organic and inorganic chemistry, in research and industry.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] It is used in quality control, dynamic measurement, and monitoring applications such as the long-term unattended measurement of CO2 concentrations in greenhouses and growth chambers by infrared gas analyzers.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] It is also used in forensic analysis in both criminal and civil cases, for example in identifying polymer degradation.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] It can be used in determining the blood alcohol content of a suspected drunk driver.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] IR spectroscopy has been used in identification of pigments in paintings and other art objects such as illuminated manuscripts.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Infrared spectroscopy is also useful in measuring the degree of polymerization in polymer manufacture.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Changes in the character or quantity of a particular bond are assessed by measuring at a specific frequency over time.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Instruments can routinely record many spectra per second in situ, providing insights into reaction mechanism (e.g., detection of intermediates) and reaction progress.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Infrared spectroscopy is utilized in the field of semiconductor microelectronics: for example, infrared spectroscopy can be applied to semiconductors like silicon, gallium arsenide, gallium nitride, zinc selenide, amorphous silicon, silicon nitride, etc.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Another important application of infrared spectroscopy is in the food industry to measure the concentration of various compounds in different food products.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Infrared spectroscopy is also used in gas leak detection devices such as the DP-IR and EyeCGAs.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] These devices detect hydrocarbon gas leaks in the transportation of natural gas and crude oil.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Infrared spectroscopy is an important analysis method in the recycling process of household waste plastics, and a convenient stand-off method to sort plastic of different polymers (PET, HDPE, ...).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Other developments include a miniature IR-spectrometer that's linked to a cloud based database and suitable for personal everyday use, and NIR-spectroscopic chips that can be embedded in smartphones and various gadgets.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] In catalysis research it is a very useful tool to characterize the catalyst, as well as to detect intermediates.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Infrared spectroscopy coupled with machine learning and artificial intelligence also has potential for rapid, accurate and non-invasive sensing of bacteria.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The complex chemical composition of bacteria, including nucleic acids, proteins, carbohydrates and fatty acids, results in high-dimensional datasets where the essential features are effectively hidden under the total spectrum.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Extraction of the essential features therefore requires advanced statistical methods such as machine learning and deep-neural networks.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The main limitation of this technique for clinical applications is the high sensitivity to technical equipment and sample preparation techniques, which makes it difficult to construct large-scale databases.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Attempts in this direction have however been made by Bruker with the IR Biotyper for food microbiology.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Infrared spectroscopy exploits the fact that molecules absorb frequencies that are characteristic of their structure.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] These absorptions occur at resonant frequencies, i.e. the frequency of the absorbed radiation matches the vibrational frequency.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The energies are affected by the shape of the molecular potential energy surfaces, the masses of the atoms, and the associated vibronic coupling.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Thus, it depends on both the nature of the bonds and the mass of the atoms that are involved.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The compression and extension of a bond may be likened to the behaviour of a spring, but real molecules are hardly perfectly elastic in nature.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] If a bond between atoms is stretched, for instance, there comes a point at which the bond breaks and the molecule dissociates into atoms.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Thus real molecules deviate from perfect harmonic motion and their molecular vibrational motion is anharmonic.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] An empirical expression that fits the energy curve of a diatomic molecule undergoing anharmonic extension and compression to a good approximation was derived by P.M.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Morse, and is called the Morse function.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] In order for a vibrational mode in a sample to be "IR active", it must be associated with changes in the molecular dipole moment.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] A permanent dipole is not necessary, as the rule requires only a *change* in dipole moment.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] A molecule can vibrate in many ways, and each way is called a **vibrational mode**.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] For molecules with N number of atoms, geometrically linear molecules have 3*N* – 5 degrees of vibrational modes, whereas nonlinear molecules have 3*N* – 6 degrees of vibrational modes (also called vibrational degrees of freedom).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] As examples linear carbon dioxide (CO2) has 3 × 3 – 5 = 4, while non-linear water (H2O), has only 3 × 3 – 6 = 3.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Simple diatomic molecules have only one bond and only one vibrational band.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] N2, the band is not observed in the IR spectrum, but only in the Raman spectrum.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Asymmetrical diatomic molecules, e.g. carbon monoxide (CO), absorb in the IR spectrum.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] More complex molecules have many bonds, and their vibrational spectra are correspondingly more complex, i.e. big molecules have many peaks in their IR spectra.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The atoms in a CH2X2 group, commonly found in organic compounds and where X can represent any other atom, can vibrate in nine different ways.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Six of these vibrations involve only the CH2 portion: two **stretching** modes (ν): **symmetric** (νs) and **antisymmetric** (νas); and four **bending** modes: **scissoring** (δ), **rocking** (ρ), **wagging** (ω) and **twisting** (τ), as shown below.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Structures that do not have the two additional X groups attached have fewer modes because some modes are defined by specific relationships to those other attached groups.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] For example, in water, the rocking, wagging, and twisting modes do not exist because these types of motions of the H atoms represent simple rotation of the whole molecule rather than vibrations within it.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] In case of more complex molecules, **out-of-plane** (γ) vibrational modes can be also present.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] These figures do not represent the "recoil" of the C atoms, which, though necessarily present to balance the overall movements of the molecule, are much smaller than the movements of the lighter H atoms.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The simplest and most important or *fundamental* IR bands arise from the excitations of normal modes, the simplest distortions of the molecule, from the ground state with vibrational quantum number *v* = 0 to the first excited state with vibrational quantum number *v* = 1.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] In some cases, overtone bands are observed.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] An overtone band arises from the absorption of a photon leading to a direct transition from the ground state to the second excited vibrational state (*v* = 2).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Such a band appears at approximately twice the energy of the fundamental band for the same normal mode.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Some excitations, so-called *combination modes*, involve simultaneous excitation of more than one normal mode.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The phenomenon of Fermi resonance can arise when two modes are similar in energy; Fermi resonance results in an unexpected shift in energy and intensity of the bands etc.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The infrared spectrum of a sample is recorded by passing a beam of infrared light through the sample.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] When the frequency of the IR matches the vibrational frequency of a bond or collection of bonds, absorption occurs.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Examination of the transmitted light reveals how much energy was absorbed at each frequency (or wavelength).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] This measurement can be achieved by scanning the wavelength range using a monochromator.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Alternatively, the entire wavelength range is measured using a Fourier transform instrument and then a transmittance or absorbance spectrum is extracted.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] This technique is commonly used for analyzing samples with covalent bonds.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The number of bands roughly correlates with symmetry and molecular complexity.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] A variety of devices are used to hold the sample in the path of the IR beam These devices are selected on the basis of their transparency in the region of interest and their resilience toward the sample.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Gaseous samples require a sample cell with a long pathlength to compensate for the diluteness.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The pathlength of the sample cell depends on the concentration of the compound of interest.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] A simple glass tube with length of 5 to 10 cm equipped with infrared-transparent windows at both ends of the tube can be used for concentrations down to several hundred ppm.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Sample gas concentrations well below ppm can be measured with a White's cell in which the infrared light is guided with mirrors to travel through the gas.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] White's cells are available with optical pathlength starting from 0.5 m up to hundred meters.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Liquid samples can be sandwiched between two plates of a salt (commonly sodium chloride, or common salt, although a number of other salts such as potassium bromide or calcium fluoride are also used).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The plates are transparent to the infrared light and do not introduce any lines onto the spectra.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] With increasing technology in computer filtering and manipulation of the results, samples in solution can now be measured accurately (water produces a broad absorbance across the range of interest, and thus renders the spectra unreadable without this computer treatment).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Solid samples can be prepared in a variety of ways.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] One common method is to crush the sample with an oily mulling agent (usually mineral oil Nujol).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] A thin film of the mull is applied onto salt plates and measured.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The second method is to grind a quantity of the sample with a specially purified salt (usually potassium bromide) finely (to remove scattering effects from large crystals).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] This powder mixture is then pressed in a mechanical press to form a translucent pellet through which the beam of the spectrometer can pass.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] A third technique is the "cast film" technique, which is used mainly for polymeric materials.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The sample is first dissolved in a suitable, non-hygroscopic solvent.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] A drop of this solution is deposited on the surface of a KBr or NaCl cell.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The solution is then evaporated to dryness and the film formed on the cell is analysed directly.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Care is important to ensure that the film is not too thick otherwise light cannot pass through.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] This technique is suitable for qualitative analysis.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The final method is to use microtomy to cut a thin (20–100 μm) film from a solid sample.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] This is one of the most important ways of analysing failed plastic products for example because the integrity of the solid is preserved.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] In photoacoustic spectroscopy the need for sample treatment is minimal.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The sample, liquid or solid, is placed into the sample cup which is inserted into the photoacoustic cell which is then sealed for the measurement.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The sample may be one solid piece, powder or basically in any form for the measurement.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] For example, a piece of rock can be inserted into the sample cup and the spectrum measured from it.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] A useful way of analyzing solid samples without the need for cutting samples uses ATR or attenuated total reflectance spectroscopy.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Using this approach, samples are pressed against the face of a single crystal.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The infrared radiation passes through the crystal and only interacts with the sample at the interface between the two materials.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] It is typical to record spectrum of both the sample and a "reference".
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] This step controls for a number of variables, e.g. infrared detector, which may affect the spectrum.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The reference measurement makes it possible to eliminate the instrument influence.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The appropriate "reference" depends on the measurement and its goal.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The simplest reference measurement is to simply remove the sample (replacing it by air).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] However, sometimes a different reference is more useful.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] For example, if the sample is a dilute solute dissolved in water in a beaker, then a good reference measurement might be to measure pure water in the same beaker.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Then the reference measurement would cancel out not only all the instrumental properties (like what light source is used), but also the light-absorbing and light-reflecting properties of the water and beaker, and the final result would just show the properties of the solute (at least approximately).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] A common way to compare to a reference is sequentially: first measure the reference, then replace the reference by the sample and measure the sample.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] This technique is not perfectly reliable; if the infrared lamp is a bit brighter during the reference measurement, then a bit dimmer during the sample measurement, the measurement will be distorted.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] More elaborate methods, such as a "two-beam" setup (see figure), can correct for these types of effects to give very accurate results.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The Standard addition method can be used to statistically cancel these errors.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Nevertheless, among different absorption-based techniques which are used for gaseous species detection, Cavity ring-down spectroscopy (CRDS) can be used as a calibration-free method.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Some instruments also automatically identify the substance being measured from a store of thousands of reference spectra held in storage.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] An alternate method for acquiring spectra is the "dispersive" or "scanning monochromator" method.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] In this approach, the sample is irradiated sequentially with various single wavelengths.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The dispersive method is more common in UV-Vis spectroscopy, but is less practical in the infrared than the FTIR method.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] One reason that FTIR is favored is called "Fellgett's advantage" or the "multiplex advantage": The information at all frequencies is collected simultaneously, improving both speed and signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Another is called "Jacquinot's Throughput Advantage": A dispersive measurement requires detecting much lower light levels than an FTIR measurement.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] There are other advantages, as well as some disadvantages, but virtually all modern infrared spectrometers are FTIR instruments.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Various forms of infrared microscopy exist.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] These include IR versions of sub-diffraction microscopy such as IR NSOM, photothermal microspectroscopy, Nano-FTIR and atomic force microscope based infrared spectroscopy (AFM-IR).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Infrared spectroscopy is not the only method of studying molecular vibrational spectra.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Raman spectroscopy involves an inelastic scattering process in which only part of the energy of an incident photon is absorbed by the molecule, and the remaining part is scattered and detected.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The energy difference corresponds to absorbed vibrational energy.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The selection rules for infrared and for Raman spectroscopy are different at least for some molecular symmetries, so that the two methods are complementary in that they observe vibrations of different symmetries.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Another method is electron energy loss spectroscopy (EELS), in which the energy absorbed is provided by an inelastically scattered electron rather than a photon.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] This method is useful for studying vibrations of molecules adsorbed on a solid surface.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] high-resolution EELS (HREELS) is a technique for performing vibrational spectroscopy in a transmission electron microscope (TEM).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Analysis of vibrational modes that are IR-inactive but appear in inelastic neutron scattering is also possible at high spatial resolution using EELS.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] By using computer simulations and normal mode analysis it is possible to calculate theoretical frequencies of molecules.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] IR spectroscopy is often used to identify structures because functional groups give rise to characteristic bands both in terms of intensity and position (frequency).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The positions of these bands are summarized in correlation tables as shown below.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] A spectrograph is often interpreted as having two regions.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] In the functional region there are one to a few troughs per functional group.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] In the fingerprint region there are many troughs which form an intricate pattern which can be used like a fingerprint to determine the compound.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] For many kinds of samples, the assignments are known, i.e. which bond deformation(s) are associated with which frequency.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] In such cases further information can be gleaned about the strength on a bond, relying on the empirical guideline called **Badger's rule**.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Originally published by Richard McLean Badger in 1934, this rule states that the strength of a bond (in terms of force constant) correlates with the bond length.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] That is, increase in bond strength leads to corresponding bond shortening and vice versa.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The different isotopes in a particular species may exhibit different fine details in infrared spectroscopy.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] For example, the O–O stretching frequency (in reciprocal centimeters) of oxyhemocyanin is experimentally determined to be 832 and 788 cm−1 for ν(16O–16O) and ν(18O–18O), respectively.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The reduced masses for 16O–16O and 18O–18O can be approximated as 8 and 9 respectively.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The effect of isotopes, both on the vibration and the decay dynamics, has been found to be stronger than previously thought.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] In some systems, such as silicon and germanium, the decay of the anti-symmetric stretch mode of interstitial oxygen involves the symmetric stretch mode with a strong isotope dependence.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] For example, it was shown that for a natural silicon sample, the lifetime of the anti-symmetric vibration is 11.4 ps.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] When the isotope of one of the silicon atoms is increased to 29Si, the lifetime increases to 19 ps.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] In similar manner, when the silicon atom is changed to 30Si, the lifetime becomes 27 ps.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] As with two-dimensional nuclear magnetic resonance (2DNMR) spectroscopy, this technique spreads the spectrum in two dimensions and allows for the observation of cross peaks that contain information on the coupling between different modes.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] In contrast to 2DNMR, nonlinear two-dimensional infrared spectroscopy also involves the excitation to overtones.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] These excitations result in excited state absorption peaks located below the diagonal and cross peaks.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] In 2DNMR, two distinct techniques, COSY and NOESY, are frequently used.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The cross peaks in the first are related to the scalar coupling, while in the latter they are related to the spin transfer between different nuclei.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] In nonlinear two-dimensional infrared spectroscopy, analogs have been drawn to these 2DNMR techniques.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] Nonlinear two-dimensional infrared spectroscopy with zero waiting time corresponds to COSY, and nonlinear two-dimensional infrared spectroscopy with finite waiting time allowing vibrational population transfer corresponds to NOESY.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/infrared-spectroscopy] The COSY variant of nonlinear two-dimensional infrared spectroscopy has been used for determination of the secondary structure content of proteins.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] A **molecular vibration** is a periodic motion of the atoms of a molecule relative to each other, such that the center of mass of the molecule remains unchanged.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The typical **vibrational frequencies** range from less than 1013 Hz to approximately 1014 Hz, corresponding to wavenumbers of approximately 300 to 3000 cm−1 and wavelengths of approximately 30 to 3 μm.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Vibrations of polyatomic molecules are described in terms of normal modes, which are independent of each other, but each normal mode involves simultaneous vibrations of parts of the molecule.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In general, a non-linear molecule with *N* atoms has 3*N* − 6 normal modes of vibration, but a *linear* molecule has 3*N* − 5 modes, because rotation about the molecular axis cannot be observed.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] A diatomic molecule has one normal mode of vibration, since it can only stretch or compress the single bond.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] A molecular vibration is excited when the molecule absorbs energy, Δ*E*, corresponding to the vibration's frequency, *ν*, according to the relation Δ*E* = *hν*, where *h* is the Planck constant.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] A fundamental vibration is evoked when one such quantum of energy is absorbed by the molecule in its ground state.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] When multiple quanta are absorbed, the first and possibly higher overtones are excited.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] To a first approximation, the motion in a normal vibration can be described as a kind of simple harmonic motion.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In this approximation, the vibrational energy is a quadratic function (parabola) with respect to the atomic displacements and the first overtone has twice the frequency of the fundamental.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In reality, vibrations are anharmonic and the first overtone has a frequency that is slightly lower than twice that of the fundamental.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Excitation of the higher overtones involves progressively less and less additional energy and eventually leads to dissociation of the molecule, because the potential energy of the molecule is more like a Morse potential or more accurately, a Morse/Long-range potential.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The vibrational states of a molecule can be probed in a variety of ways.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The most direct way is through infrared spectroscopy, as vibrational transitions typically require an amount of energy that corresponds to the infrared region of the spectrum.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Raman spectroscopy, which typically uses visible light, can also be used to measure vibration frequencies directly.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The two techniques are complementary and comparison between the two can provide useful structural information such as in the case of the rule of mutual exclusion for centrosymmetric molecules.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Vibrational excitation can occur in conjunction with electronic excitation in the ultraviolet-visible region.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The combined excitation is known as a vibronic transition, giving vibrational fine structure to electronic transitions, particularly for molecules in the gas state.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Simultaneous excitation of a vibration and rotations gives rise to vibration–rotation spectra.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] For a molecule with N atoms, the positions of all N nuclei depend on a total of 3N coordinates, so that the molecule has 3N degrees of freedom including translation, rotation and vibration.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Translation corresponds to movement of the center of mass whose position can be described by 3 cartesian coordinates.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] A nonlinear molecule can rotate about any of three mutually perpendicular axes and therefore has 3 rotational degrees of freedom.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] For a linear molecule, rotation about the molecular axis does not involve movement of any atomic nucleus, so there are only 2 rotational degrees of freedom which can vary the atomic coordinates.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] An equivalent argument is that the rotation of a linear molecule changes the direction of the molecular axis in space, which can be described by 2 coordinates corresponding to latitude and longitude.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] For a nonlinear molecule, the direction of one axis is described by these two coordinates, and the orientation of the molecule about this axis provides a third rotational coordinate.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The number of vibrational modes is therefore 3N minus the number of translational and rotational degrees of freedom, or 3N − 5 for linear and 3N − 6 for nonlinear molecules.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The coordinate of a normal vibration is a combination of *changes* in the positions of atoms in the molecule.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] When the vibration is excited the coordinate changes sinusoidally with a frequency ν, the frequency of the vibration.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In a rocking, wagging or twisting coordinate the bond lengths within the groups involved do not change.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Rocking is distinguished from wagging by the fact that the atoms in the group stay in the same plane.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In ethylene there are 12 internal coordinates: 4 C–H stretching, 1 C–C stretching, 2 H–C–H bending, 2 CH2 rocking, 2 CH2 wagging, 1 twisting.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Note that the H–C–C angles cannot be used as internal coordinates as well as the H–C–H angle because the angles at each carbon atom cannot all increase at the same time.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Note that these coordinates do not correspond to normal modes (see *§ Normal coordinates*).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In other words, they do not correspond to particular frequencies or vibrational transitions.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Within the CH2 group, commonly found in organic compounds, the two low mass hydrogens can vibrate in six different ways which can be grouped as 3 pairs of modes: 1.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] **symmetric** and **asymmetric stretching**, 2.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] (These figures do not represent the "recoil" of the C atoms, which, though necessarily present to balance the overall movements of the molecule, are much smaller than the movements of the lighter H atoms).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Symmetry–adapted coordinates may be created by applying a projection operator to a set of internal coordinates.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The projection operator is constructed with the aid of the character table of the molecular point group.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Illustrations of symmetry–adapted coordinates for most small molecules can be found in Nakamoto.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The normal coordinates, denoted as *Q*, refer to the positions of atoms away from their equilibrium positions, with respect to a normal mode of vibration.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Each normal mode is assigned a single normal coordinate, and so the normal coordinate refers to the "progress" along that normal mode at any given time.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Formally, normal modes are determined by solving a secular determinant, and then the normal coordinates (over the normal modes) can be expressed as a summation over the cartesian coordinates (over the atom positions).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The normal modes diagonalize the matrix governing the molecular vibrations, so that each normal mode is an independent molecular vibration.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] If the molecule possesses symmetries, the normal modes "transform as" an irreducible representation under its point group.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The normal modes are determined by applying group theory, and projecting the irreducible representation onto the cartesian coordinates.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] When two or more normal coordinates belong to the same irreducible representation of the molecular point group (colloquially, have the same symmetry) there is "mixing" and the coefficients of the combination cannot be determined *a priori*.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The coefficients a and b are found by performing a full normal coordinate analysis by means of the Wilson GF method.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Perhaps surprisingly, molecular vibrations can be treated using Newtonian mechanics to calculate the correct vibration frequencies.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The basic assumption is that each vibration can be treated as though it corresponds to a spring.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In the harmonic approximation the spring obeys Hooke's law: the force required to extend the spring is proportional to the extension.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The proportionality constant is known as a *force constant, k*.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] It remains to define the reduced mass, *μ*.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In general, the reduced mass of a diatomic molecule, AB, is expressed in terms of the atomic masses, *mA* and *mB*, as ${\frac {1}{\mu }}={\frac {1}{m_{A}}}+{\frac {1}{m_{B}}}.$ The use of the reduced mass ensures that the centre of mass of the molecule is not affected by the vibration.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In the harmonic approximation the potential energy of the molecule is a quadratic function of the normal coordinate.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] When two or more normal vibrations have the same symmetry a full normal coordinate analysis must be performed (see GF method).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The vibration frequencies, *ν**i*, are obtained from the eigenvalues, *λ**i*, of the matrix product ***GF***.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] ***G*** is a matrix of numbers derived from the masses of the atoms and the geometry of the molecule.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] ***F*** is a matrix derived from force-constant values.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Details concerning the determination of the eigenvalues can be found in.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In the harmonic approximation the potential energy is a quadratic function of the normal coordinates.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Solving the Schrödinger wave equation, the energy states for each normal coordinate are given by $E_{n}=h\left(n+{1 \over 2}\right)\nu =h\left(n+{1 \over 2}\right){1 \over {2\pi }}{\sqrt {k \over m}},$ where *n* is a quantum number that can take values of 0, 1, 2, ...
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In molecular spectroscopy where several types of molecular energy are studied and several quantum numbers are used, this *vibrational quantum number* is often designated as *v*.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] The difference in energy when *n* (or *v*) changes by 1 is therefore equal to $h\nu$ , the product of the Planck constant and the vibration frequency derived using classical mechanics.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] For a transition from level *n* to level *n+1* due to absorption of a photon, the frequency of the photon is equal to the classical vibration frequency $\nu$ (in the harmonic oscillator approximation).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] See quantum harmonic oscillator for graphs of the first 5 wave functions, which allow certain selection rules to be formulated.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] For example, for a harmonic oscillator transitions are allowed only when the quantum number *n* changes by one, $\Delta n=\pm 1$ but this does not apply to an anharmonic oscillator; the observation of overtones is only possible because vibrations are anharmonic.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Another consequence of anharmonicity is that transitions such as between states *n* = 2 and *n* = 1 have slightly less energy than transitions between the ground state and first excited state.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Such a transition gives rise to a hot band.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] To describe vibrational levels of an anharmonic oscillator, Dunham expansion is used.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] When it comes to polyatomic molecules, it is common to solve the Schrödinger Equation using Watson's nuclear motion Hamiltonian.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Similar as for diatomics, this can be done within the harmonic approximation as stated above.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] For the anharmonic calculation of vibrational spectra of polyatomic molecules, more sophisticated approaches are used.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Prominent examples in computational chemistry are 2nd order vibrational perturbation theory (VPT2) or vibrational configuration interaction theory (VCI).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] In an infrared spectrum the intensity of an absorption band is proportional to the derivative of the molecular dipole moment with respect to the normal coordinate.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] Likewise, the intensity of Raman bands depends on the derivative of polarizability with respect to the normal coordinate.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/molecular-vibration] There is also a dependence on the fourth-power of the wavelength of the laser used.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Near-infrared spectroscopy is based on molecular overtone and combination vibrations.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Overtones and combinations exhibit lower intensity compared to the fundamental, as a result, the molar absorptivity in the near-IR region is typically quite small.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] (NIR absorption bands are typically 10–100 times weaker than the corresponding fundamental mid-IR absorption band.) The lower absorption allows NIR radiation to penetrate much further into a sample than mid infrared radiation.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Near-infrared spectroscopy is, therefore, not a particularly sensitive technique, but it can be very useful in probing bulk material with little to no sample preparation.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] The molecular overtone and combination bands seen in the near-IR are typically very broad, leading to complex spectra; it can be difficult to assign specific features to specific chemical components.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Multivariate (multiple variables) calibration techniques (e.g., principal components analysis, partial least squares, or artificial neural networks) are often employed to extract the desired chemical information.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Careful development of a set of calibration samples and application of multivariate calibration techniques is essential for near-infrared analytical methods.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] The discovery of near-infrared energy is ascribed to William Herschel in the 19th century, but the first industrial application began in the 1950s.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] In the first applications, NIRS was used only as an add-on unit to other optical devices that used other wavelengths such as ultraviolet (UV), visible (Vis), or mid-infrared (MIR) spectrometers.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] In the 1980s, a single-unit, stand-alone NIRS system was made available.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] In the 1980s, Karl Norris (while working at the USDA Instrumentation Research Laboratory, Beltsville, USA) pioneered the use NIR spectroscopy for quality assessments of agricultural products.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Since then, use has expanded from food and agricultural to chemical, polymer, and petroleum industries; pharmaceutical industry; biomedical sciences; and environmental analysis.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] With the introduction of light-fiber optics in the mid-1980s and the monochromator-detector developments in the early 1990s, NIRS became a more powerful tool for scientific research.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] The method has been used in a number of fields of science including physics, physiology, or medicine.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] It is only in the last few decades that NIRS began to be used as a medical tool for monitoring patients, with the first clinical application of so-called fNIRS in 1994.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Instrumentation for near-IR (NIR) spectroscopy is similar to instruments for the UV-visible and mid-IR ranges.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] There is a source, a detector, and a dispersive element (such as a prism, or, more commonly, a diffraction grating) to allow the intensity at different wavelengths to be recorded.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Fourier transform NIR instruments using an interferometer are also common, especially for wavelengths above ~1000 nm.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Depending on the sample, the spectrum can be measured in either reflection or transmission.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Common incandescent or quartz halogen light bulbs are most often used as broadband sources of near-infrared radiation for analytical applications.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Light-emitting diodes (LEDs) can also be used.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] For high precision spectroscopy, wavelength-scanned lasers and frequency combs have recently become powerful sources, albeit with sometimes longer acquisition timescales.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] When lasers are used, a single detector without any dispersive elements might be sufficient.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] The type of detector used depends primarily on the range of wavelengths to be measured.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Silicon-based CCDs are suitable for the shorter end of the NIR range, but are not sufficiently sensitive over most of the range (over 1000 nm).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] InGaAs and PbS devices are more suitable and have higher quantum efficiency for wavelengths above 1100 nm.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] It is possible to combine silicon-based and InGaAs detectors in the same instrument.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Such instruments can record both UV-visible and NIR spectra 'simultaneously'.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Instruments intended for chemical imaging in the NIR may use a 2D array detector with an acousto-optic tunable filter.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Multiple images may be recorded sequentially at different narrow wavelength bands.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Many commercial instruments for UV/vis spectroscopy are capable of recording spectra in the NIR range (to perhaps ~900 nm).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] In the same way, the range of some mid-IR instruments may extend into the NIR.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] In these instruments, the detector used for the NIR wavelengths is often the same detector used for the instrument's "main" range of interest.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] The use of NIR as an analytical technique did not come from extending the use of mid-IR into the near-IR range, but developed independently.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] A striking way this was exhibited is that, while mid-IR spectroscopists use wavenumbers (*cm*−1) when displaying spectra, NIR spectroscopists used wavelength (*nm*), as is used in ultraviolet–visible spectroscopy.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Early practitioners of IR spectroscopy, who depended on assignment of absorption bands to specific bond types, were frustrated by the complexity of the bonding regions being measured.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] However, as a quantitative tool, the lower molar absorption levels in the bonding region tended to keep absorption maxima "on-scale", enabling quantitative work with little sample preparation.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Techniques applied to extract the quantitative information from these complex spectra were unfamiliar to analytical chemists, and the technique was viewed with suspicion in academia.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] The calibration is then validated by using it to predict the analyte values for samples in a validation set, whose values have been determined by the reference method but have not been included in the calibration.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] A validated calibration is then used to predict the values of samples.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] The complexity of the spectra are overcome by the use of multivariate calibration.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] The two tools most often used a multi-wavelength linear regression and partial least squares.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Typical applications of NIR spectroscopy include the analysis of food products, pharmaceuticals, combustion products, and a major branch of astronomical spectroscopy.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Near-infrared spectroscopy is used in astronomy for studying the atmospheres of cool stars where molecules can form.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] The vibrational and rotational signatures of molecules such as titanium oxide, cyanide, and carbon monoxide can be seen in this wavelength range and can give a clue towards the star's spectral type.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] It is also used for studying molecules in other astronomical contexts, such as in molecular clouds where new stars are formed.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] The astronomical phenomenon known as reddening means that near-infrared wavelengths are less affected by dust in the interstellar medium, such that regions inaccessible by optical spectroscopy can be studied in the near-infrared.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Since dust and gas are strongly associated, these dusty regions are exactly those where infrared spectroscopy is most useful.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] The near-infrared spectra of very young stars provide important information about their ages and masses, which is important for understanding star formation in general.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Astronomical spectrographs have also been developed for the detection of exoplanets using the Doppler shift of the parent star due to the radial velocity of the planet around the star.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Near-infrared spectroscopy is widely applied in agriculture for determining the quality of forages, grains, and grain products, oilseeds, coffee, tea, spices, fruits, vegetables, sugarcane, beverages, fats, and oils, dairy products, eggs, meat, and other agricultural products.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] It is widely used to quantify the composition of agricultural products because it meets the criteria of being accurate, reliable, rapid, non-destructive, and inexpensive.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Abeni and Bergoglio 2001 apply NIRS to chicken breeding as the assay method for characteristics of fat composition.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Techniques have been developed for NIR spectroscopic imaging.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Hyperspectral imaging has been applied for a wide range of uses, including the remote investigation of plants and soils.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Data can be collected from instruments on airplanes, satellites or unmanned aerial systems to assess ground cover and soil chemistry.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Remote monitoring or remote sensing from the NIR spectroscopic region can also be used to study the atmosphere.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] For example, measurements of atmospheric gases are made from NIR spectra measured by the OCO-2, GOSAT, and the TCCON.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Techniques have been developed for NIR spectroscopy of microscopic sample areas for film thickness measurements, research into the optical characteristics of nanoparticles and optical coatings for the telecommunications industry.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] The application of NIRS in medicine centres on its ability to provide information about the oxygen saturation of haemoglobin within the microcirculation.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Broadly speaking, it can be used to assess oxygenation and microvascular function in the brain (cerebral NIRS) or in the peripheral tissues (peripheral NIRS).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] When a specific area of the brain is activated, the localized blood volume in that area changes quickly.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Optical imaging can measure the location and activity of specific regions of the brain by continuously monitoring blood hemoglobin levels through the determination of optical absorption coefficients.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] NIRS can be used as a quick screening tool for possible intracranial bleeding cases by placing the scanner on four locations on the head.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] In non-injured patients the brain absorbs the NIR light evenly.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] When there is an internal bleeding from an injury, the blood may be concentrated in one location causing the NIR light to be absorbed more than other locations, which the scanner detects.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] NIRS can be used on infants, and NIRS is much more portable than fMRI machines, even wireless instrumentation is available, which enables investigations in freely moving subjects.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] However, NIRS cannot fully replace fMRI because it can only be used to scan cortical tissue, whereas fMRI can be used to measure activation throughout the brain.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Special public domain statistical toolboxes for analysis of stand alone and combined NIRS/MRI measurement have been developed.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] The application in functional mapping of the human cortex is called functional NIRS (fNIRS) or diffuse optical tomography (DOT).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] The term diffuse optical tomography is used for three-dimensional NIRS.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] The terms NIRS, NIRI, and DOT are often used interchangeably, but they have some distinctions.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] The latter is also used to investigate other tissues such as, e.g., muscle, breast and tumors.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] NIRS can be used to quantify blood flow, blood volume, oxygen consumption, reoxygenation rates and muscle recovery time in muscle.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] By employing several wavelengths and time resolved (frequency or time domain) and/or spatially resolved methods blood flow, volume and absolute tissue saturation ( $StO_{2}$ or Tissue Saturation Index (TSI)) can be quantified.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] The use of NIRS in conjunction with a bolus injection of indocyanine green (ICG) has been used to measure cerebral blood flow and cerebral metabolic rate of oxygen consumption (CMRO2).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] It has also been shown that CMRO2 can be calculated with combined NIRS/MRI measurements.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Additionally metabolism can be interrogated by resolving an additional mitochondrial chromophore, cytochrome-c-oxidase, using broadband NIRS.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] NIRS is starting to be used in pediatric critical care, to help manage patients following cardiac surgery.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Indeed, NIRS is able to measure venous oxygen saturation (SVO2), which is determined by the cardiac output, as well as other parameters (FiO2, hemoglobin, oxygen uptake).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Therefore, examining the NIRS provides critical care physicians with an estimate of the cardiac output.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] NIRS is favoured by patients, because it is non-invasive, painless, and does not require ionizing radiation.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Optical coherence tomography (OCT) is another NIR medical imaging technique capable of 3D imaging with high resolution on par with low-power microscopy.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Using optical coherence to measure photon pathlength allows OCT to build images of live tissue and clear examinations of tissue morphology.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Due to technique differences OCT is limited to imaging 1–2 mm below tissue surfaces, but despite this limitation OCT has become an established medical imaging technique especially for imaging of the retina and anterior segments of the eye, as well as coronaries.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] A type of neurofeedback, hemoencephalography or HEG, uses NIR technology to measure brain activation, primarily of the frontal lobes, for the purpose of training cerebral activation of that region.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] The instrumental development of NIRS/NIRI/DOT/OCT has proceeded tremendously during the last years and, in particular, in terms of quantification, imaging and miniaturization.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Peripheral microvascular function can be assessed using NIRS.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] The oxygen saturation of haemoglobin in the tissue (StO2) can provide information about tissue perfusion.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] A vascular occlusion test (VOT) can be employed to assess microvascular function.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Common sites for peripheral NIRS monitoring include the thenar eminence, forearm and calf muscles.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] NIR is often used in particle sizing in a range of different fields, including studying pharmaceutical and agricultural powders.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] As opposed to NIRS used in optical topography, general NIRS used in chemical assays does not provide imaging by mapping.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] For example, a clinical carbon dioxide analyzer requires reference techniques and calibration routines to be able to get accurate CO2 content change.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] In this case, calibration is performed by adjusting the zero control of the sample being tested after purposefully supplying 0% CO2 or another known amount of CO2 in the sample.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/near-infrared-spectroscopy] Normal compressed gas from distributors contains about 95% O2 and 5% CO2, which can also be used to adjust %CO2 meter reading to be exactly 5% at initial calibration.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] A **normal mode** of a dynamical system is a pattern of motion in which all parts of the system move sinusoidally with the same frequency and with a fixed phase relation.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] The free motion described by the normal modes takes place at fixed frequencies.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] These fixed frequencies of the normal modes of a system are known as its natural frequencies or resonant frequencies.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] A physical object, such as a building, bridge, or molecule, has a set of normal modes and their natural frequencies that depend on its structure, materials and boundary conditions.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] The most general motion of a linear system is a superposition of its normal modes.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] The modes are "normal" in the sense that they move independently.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] An excitation of one mode will never cause excitation of a different mode.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] In mathematical terms, normal modes are orthogonal to each other.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] In the wave theory of physics and engineering, a **mode** in a dynamical system is a standing wave state of excitation, in which all the components of the system will be affected sinusoidally at a fixed frequency associated with that mode.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Because no real system can perfectly fit under the standing wave framework, the *mode* concept is taken as a general characterization of specific states of oscillation, thus treating the dynamic system in a *linear* fashion, in which linear superposition of states can be performed.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] The concept of normal modes also finds application in other dynamical systems, such as optics, quantum mechanics, atmospheric dynamics and molecular dynamics.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Most dynamical systems can be excited in several modes, possibly simultaneously.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Each mode is characterized by one or several frequencies, according to the modal variable field.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] For example, a vibrating rope in 2D space is defined by a single-frequency (1D axial displacement), but a vibrating rope in 3D space is defined by two frequencies (2D axial displacement).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] For a given amplitude on the modal variable, each mode will store a specific amount of energy because of the sinusoidal excitation.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] A mode of vibration is characterized by a modal frequency and a mode shape.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] It is numbered according to the number of half waves in the vibration.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] For example, if a vibrating beam with both ends pinned displayed a mode shape of half of a sine wave (one peak on the vibrating beam) it would be vibrating in mode 1.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] If it had a full sine wave (one peak and one trough) it would be vibrating in mode 2.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] In a system with two or more dimensions, such as the pictured disk, each dimension is given a mode number.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Using polar coordinates, we have a radial coordinate and an angular coordinate.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] If one measured from the center outward along the radial coordinate one would encounter a full wave, so the mode number in the radial direction is 2.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] The other direction is trickier, because only half of the disk is considered due to the anti-symmetric (also called skew-symmetry) nature of a disk's vibration in the angular direction.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Thus, measuring 180° along the angular direction you would encounter a half wave, so the mode number in the angular direction is 1.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] So the mode number of the system is 2–1 or 1–2, depending on which coordinate is considered the "first" and which is considered the "second" coordinate (so it is important to always indicate which mode number matches with each coordinate direction).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] In linear systems each mode is entirely independent of all other modes.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] In general all modes have different frequencies (with lower modes having lower frequencies) and different mode shapes.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] In a one-dimensional system at a given mode the vibration will have nodes, or places where the displacement is always zero.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] These nodes correspond to points in the mode shape where the mode shape is zero.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Since the vibration of a system is given by the mode shape multiplied by a time function, the displacement of the node points remain zero at all times.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] When expanded to a two dimensional system, these nodes become lines where the displacement is always zero.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] If you watch the animation above you will see two circles (one about halfway between the edge and center, and the other on the edge itself) and a straight line bisecting the disk, where the displacement is close to zero.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] In an idealized system these lines equal zero exactly, as shown to the right.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Consider two equal bodies (not affected by gravity), each of mass m, attached to three springs, each with spring constant k.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] where the edge points are fixed and cannot move.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Let *x*1(*t*) denote the horizontal displacement of the left mass, and *x*2(*t*) denote the displacement of the right mass.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] If the matrix on the left is invertible, the unique solution is the trivial solution (*A*1, *A*2) = (*x*1, *x*2) = (0, 0).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] The non trivial solutions are to be found for those values of ω whereby the matrix on the left is singular; i.e. is not invertible.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Substituting *ω*1 into the matrix and solving for (*A*1, *A*2), yields (1, 1).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Which corresponds to both masses moving in the same direction at the same time.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] This corresponds to the masses moving in the opposite directions, while the center of mass remains stationary.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] The general solution is a superposition of the **normal modes** where *c*1, *c*2, *φ*1, and *φ*2 are determined by the initial conditions of the problem.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] The process demonstrated here can be generalized and formulated using the formalism of Lagrangian mechanics or Hamiltonian mechanics.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] A standing wave is a continuous form of normal mode.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] In a standing wave, all the space elements (i.e.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] (*x*, *y*, *z*) coordinates) are oscillating in the same frequency and in phase (reaching the equilibrium point together), but each has a different amplitude.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] where *f*(*x*, *y*, *z*) represents the dependence of amplitude on location and the cosine/sine are the oscillations in time.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Physically, standing waves are formed by the interference (superposition) of waves and their reflections (although one may also say the opposite; that a moving wave is a superposition of standing waves).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] The geometric shape of the medium determines what would be the interference pattern, thus determines the *f*(*x*, *y*, *z*) form of the standing wave.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] This space-dependence is called a **normal mode**.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Usually, for problems with continuous dependence on (*x*, *y*, *z*) there is no single or finite number of normal modes, but there are infinitely many normal modes.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] If the problem is bounded (i.e. it is defined on a finite section of space) there are countably many normal modes (usually numbered *n* = 1, 2, 3, ...).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] If the problem is not bounded, there is a continuous spectrum of normal modes.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] In any solid at any temperature, the primary particles (e.g. atoms or molecules) are not stationary, but rather vibrate about mean positions.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] In insulators the capacity of the solid to store thermal energy is due almost entirely to these vibrations.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Many physical properties of the solid (e.g. modulus of elasticity) can be predicted given knowledge of the frequencies with which the particles vibrate.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] The simplest assumption (by Einstein) is that all the particles oscillate about their mean positions with the same natural frequency ν.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] This is equivalent to the assumption that all atoms vibrate independently with a frequency ν.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Einstein also assumed that the allowed energy states of these oscillations are harmonics, or integral multiples of hν.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] The spectrum of waveforms can be described mathematically using a Fourier series of sinusoidal density fluctuations (or thermal phonons).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Debye subsequently recognized that each oscillator is intimately coupled to its neighboring oscillators at all times.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Thus, by replacing Einstein's identical uncoupled oscillators with the same number of coupled oscillators, Debye correlated the elastic vibrations of a one-dimensional solid with the number of mathematically special modes of vibration of a stretched string (see figure).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] The pure tone of lowest pitch or frequency is referred to as the fundamental and the multiples of that frequency are called its harmonic overtones.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] He assigned to one of the oscillators the frequency of the fundamental vibration of the whole block of solid.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] He assigned to the remaining oscillators the frequencies of the harmonics of that fundamental, with the highest of all these frequencies being limited by the motion of the smallest primary unit.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] The normal modes of vibration of a crystal are in general superpositions of many overtones, each with an appropriate amplitude and phase.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Longer wavelength (low frequency) phonons are exactly those acoustical vibrations which are considered in the theory of sound.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Both longitudinal and transverse waves can be propagated through a solid, while, in general, only longitudinal waves are supported by fluids.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] In the longitudinal mode, the displacement of particles from their positions of equilibrium coincides with the propagation direction of the wave.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Mechanical longitudinal waves have been also referred to as **compression waves**.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] For transverse modes, individual particles move perpendicular to the propagation of the wave.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] The term (1/2)*hν* represents the "zero-point energy", or the energy which an oscillator will have at absolute zero.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] In order to calculate the internal energy and the specific heat, we must know the number of normal vibrational modes a frequency between the values ν and *ν* + *dν*.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] The integration is performed over all frequencies of the crystal.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Bound states in quantum mechanics are analogous to modes.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] The waves in quantum systems are oscillations in probability amplitude rather than material displacement.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] The frequency of oscillation, f, relates to the mode energy by *E* = *hf* where h is the Planck constant.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Thus a system like an atom consists of a linear combination of modes of definite energy.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] These energies are characteristic of the particular atom.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] The (complex) square of the probability amplitude at a point in space gives the probability of measuring an electron at that location.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] The spatial distribution of this probability is characteristic of the atom.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Normal modes are generated in the Earth from long wavelength seismic waves from large earthquakes interfering to form standing waves.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] For an elastic, isotropic, homogeneous sphere, spheroidal, toroidal and radial (or breathing) modes arise.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Spheroidal modes only involve P and SV waves (like Rayleigh waves) and depend on overtone number n and angular order l but have degeneracy of azimuthal order m.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Increasing l concentrates fundamental branch closer to surface and at large l this tends to Rayleigh waves.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Toroidal modes only involve SH waves (like Love waves) and do not exist in fluid outer core.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Radial modes are just a subset of spheroidal modes with *l* = 0.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] The degeneracy does not exist on Earth as it is broken by rotation, ellipticity and 3D heterogeneous velocity and density structure.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] It may be assumed that each mode can be isolated, the self-coupling approximation, or that many modes close in frequency resonate, the cross-coupling approximation.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Self-coupling will solely change the phase velocity and not the number of waves around a great circle, resulting in a stretching or shrinking of standing wave pattern.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/normal-mode] Modal cross-coupling occurs due to the rotation of the Earth, from aspherical elastic structure, or due to Earth's ellipticity and leads to a mixing of fundamental spheroidal and toroidal modes.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy relies upon inelastic scattering of photons, known as Raman scattering.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] A source of monochromatic light, usually from a laser in the visible, near infrared, or near ultraviolet range is used, although X-rays can also be used.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The laser light interacts with molecular vibrations, phonons or other excitations in the system, resulting in the energy of the laser photons being shifted up or down.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The shift in energy gives information about the vibrational modes in the system.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Time-resolved spectroscopy and infrared spectroscopy typically yield similar yet complementary information.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Typically, a sample is illuminated with a laser beam.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Electromagnetic radiation from the illuminated spot is collected with a lens.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Elastic scattered radiation at the wavelength corresponding to the laser line (Rayleigh scattering) is filtered out by either a notch filter, edge pass filter, or a band pass filter, while the rest of the collected light is dispersed onto a detector.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Spontaneous Raman scattering is typically very weak.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] As a result, for many years the main difficulty in collecting Raman spectra was separating the weak inelastically scattered light from the intense Rayleigh scattered laser light (referred to as "laser rejection").
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Historically, Raman spectrometers used holographic gratings and multiple dispersion stages to achieve a high degree of laser rejection.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In the past, photomultipliers were the detectors of choice for dispersive Raman setups, which resulted in long acquisition times.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] However, modern instrumentation almost universally employs notch or edge filters for laser rejection.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Dispersive single-stage spectrographs (axial transmissive (AT) or Czerny–Turner (CT) monochromators) paired with CCD detectors are most common although Fourier transform (FT) spectrometers are also common for use with NIR lasers.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The name "Raman spectroscopy" typically refers to vibrational Raman spectroscopy using laser wavelengths which are not absorbed by the sample.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] There are many other variations of Raman spectroscopy including surface-enhanced Raman, resonance Raman, tip-enhanced Raman, polarized Raman, stimulated Raman, transmission Raman, spatially-offset Raman, and hyper Raman.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Although the inelastic scattering of light was predicted by Adolf Smekal in 1923, it was not observed in practice until 1928.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The Raman effect was named after one of its discoverers, the Indian scientist C.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman, who observed the effect in organic liquids in 1928 together with K.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Krishnan, and independently by Grigory Landsberg and Leonid Mandelstam in inorganic crystals.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman won the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1930 for this discovery.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The first observation of Raman spectra in gases was in 1929 by Franco Rasetti.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Systematic pioneering theory of the Raman effect was developed by Czechoslovak physicist George Placzek between 1930 and 1934.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The mercury arc became the principal light source, first with photographic detection and then with spectrophotometric detection.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In the years following its discovery, Raman spectroscopy was used to provide the first catalog of molecular vibrational frequencies.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Typically, the sample was held in a long tube and illuminated along its length with a beam of filtered monochromatic light generated by a gas discharge lamp.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The photons that were scattered by the sample were collected through an optical flat at the end of the tube.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] To maximize the sensitivity, the sample was highly concentrated (1 M or more) and relatively large volumes (5 mL or more) were used.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The magnitude of the Raman effect correlates with the polarizability of the electrons in a molecule.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It is a form of inelastic light scattering, where a photon excites the sample.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This excitation puts the molecule into a virtual energy state for a short time before the photon is emitted.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Inelastic scattering means that the energy of the emitted photon is of either lower or higher energy than the incident photon.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] After the scattering event, the sample is in a different rotational or vibrational state.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For the total energy of the system to remain constant after the molecule moves to a new rovibronic (rotational–vibrational–electronic) state, the scattered photon shifts to a different energy, and therefore a different frequency.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This energy difference is equal to that between the initial and final rovibronic states of the molecule.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] If the final state is higher in energy than the initial state, the scattered photon will be shifted to a lower frequency (lower energy) so that the total energy remains the same.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This shift in frequency is called a Stokes shift, or downshift.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] If the final state is lower in energy, the scattered photon will be shifted to a higher frequency, which is called an anti-Stokes shift, or upshift.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For a molecule to exhibit a Raman effect, there must be a change in its electric dipole-electric dipole polarizability with respect to the vibrational coordinate corresponding to the rovibronic state.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The intensity of the Raman scattering is proportional to this polarizability change.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Therefore, the Raman spectrum (scattering intensity as a function of the frequency shifts) depends on the rovibronic states of the molecule.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The Raman effect is based on the interaction between the electron cloud of a sample and the external electric field of the monochromatic light, which can create an induced dipole moment within the molecule based on its polarizability.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Because the laser light does not excite the molecule there can be no real transition between energy levels.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The Raman effect should not be confused with emission (fluorescence or phosphorescence), where a molecule in an excited electronic state emits a photon and returns to the ground electronic state, in many cases to a vibrationally excited state on the ground electronic state potential energy surface.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman scattering also contrasts with infrared (IR) absorption, where the energy of the absorbed photon matches the difference in energy between the initial and final rovibronic states.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The dependence of Raman on the electric dipole-electric dipole polarizability derivative also differs from IR spectroscopy, which depends on the electric dipole moment derivative, the atomic polar tensor (APT).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This contrasting feature allows rovibronic transitions that might not be active in IR to be analyzed using Raman spectroscopy, as exemplified by the rule of mutual exclusion in centrosymmetric molecules.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Transitions which have large Raman intensities often have weak IR intensities and vice versa.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] If a bond is strongly polarized, a small change in its length such as that which occurs during a vibration has only a small resultant effect on polarization.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] C-O, N-O, O-H) are therefore, comparatively weak Raman scatterers.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Such polarized bonds, however, carry their electrical charges during the vibrational motion, (unless neutralized by symmetry factors), and this results in a larger net dipole moment change during the vibration, producing a strong IR absorption band.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Conversely, relatively neutral bonds (e.g.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] C-C, C-H, C=C) suffer large changes in polarizability during a vibration.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] However, the dipole moment is not similarly affected such that while vibrations involving predominantly this type of bond are strong Raman scatterers, they are weak in the IR.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] A third vibrational spectroscopy technique, inelastic incoherent neutron scattering (IINS), can be used to determine the frequencies of vibrations in highly symmetric molecules that may be both IR and Raman inactive.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The IINS selection rules, or allowed transitions, differ from those of IR and Raman, so the three techniques are complementary.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] They all give the same frequency for a given vibrational transition, but the relative intensities provide different information due to the different types of interaction between the molecule and the incoming particles, photons for IR and Raman, and neutrons for IINS.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman shifts are typically reported in wavenumbers, which have units of inverse length, as this value is directly related to energy.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] where Δν̃ is the Raman shift expressed in wavenumber, λ0 is the excitation wavelength, and λ1 is the Raman spectrum wavelength.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Most commonly, the unit chosen for expressing wavenumber in Raman spectra is inverse centimeters (cm−1).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Modern Raman spectroscopy nearly always involves the use of lasers as excitation light sources.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Because lasers were not available until more than three decades after the discovery of the effect, Raman and Krishnan used a mercury lamp and photographic plates to record spectra.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Early spectra took hours or even days to acquire due to weak light sources, poor sensitivity of the detectors and the weak Raman scattering cross-sections of most materials.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Various colored filters and chemical solutions were used to select certain wavelength regions for excitation and detection but the photographic spectra were still dominated by a broad center line corresponding to Rayleigh scattering of the excitation source.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Technological advances have made Raman spectroscopy much more sensitive, particularly since the 1980s.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The most common modern detectors are now charge-coupled devices (CCDs).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Photodiode arrays and photomultiplier tubes were common prior to the adoption of CCDs.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The advent of reliable, stable, inexpensive lasers with narrow bandwidths has also had an impact.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy requires a light source such as a laser.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The resolution of the spectrum relies on the bandwidth of the laser source used.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Generally shorter wavelength lasers give stronger Raman scattering due to the ν4 increase in Raman scattering cross-sections, but issues with sample degradation or fluorescence may result.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Continuous wave lasers are most common for normal Raman spectroscopy, but pulsed lasers may also be used.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] These often have wider bandwidths than their CW counterparts but are very useful for other forms of Raman spectroscopy such as transient, time-resolved and resonance Raman.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman scattered light is typically collected and either dispersed by a spectrograph or used with an interferometer for detection by Fourier Transform (FT) methods.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In many cases commercially available FT-IR spectrometers can be modified to become FT-Raman spectrometers.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In most cases, modern Raman spectrometers use array detectors such as CCDs.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Various types of CCDs exist which are optimized for different wavelength ranges.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Intensified CCDs can be used for very weak signals and/or pulsed lasers.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The spectral range depends on the size of the CCD and the focal length of spectrograph used.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It was once common to use monochromators coupled to photomultiplier tubes.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In this case the monochromator would need to be moved in order to scan through a spectral range.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] FT–Raman is almost always used with NIR lasers and appropriate detectors must be used depending on the exciting wavelength.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Germanium or Indium gallium arsenide (InGaAs) detectors are commonly used.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It is usually necessary to separate the Raman scattered light from the Rayleigh signal and reflected laser signal in order to collect high quality Raman spectra using a laser rejection filter.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Notch or long-pass optical filters are typically used for this purpose.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Before the advent of holographic filters it was common to use a triple-grating monochromator in subtractive mode to isolate the desired signal.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This may still be used to record very small Raman shifts as holographic filters typically reflect some of the low frequency bands in addition to the unshifted laser light.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] However, Volume hologram filters are becoming more common which allow shifts as low as 5 cm−1 to be observed.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy is used in chemistry to identify molecules and study chemical bonding and intramolecular bonds.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Because vibrational frequencies are specific to a molecule's chemical bonds and symmetry (the fingerprint region of organic molecules is in the wavenumber range 500–1,500 cm−1), Raman provides a fingerprint to identify molecules.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For instance, Raman and IR spectra were used to determine the vibrational frequencies of SiO, Si2O2, and Si3O3 on the basis of normal coordinate analyses.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman is also used to study the addition of a substrate to an enzyme.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In solid-state physics, Raman spectroscopy is used to characterize materials, measure temperature, and find the crystallographic orientation of a sample.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] As with single molecules, a solid material can be identified by characteristic phonon modes.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Information on the population of a phonon mode is given by the ratio of the Stokes and anti-Stokes intensity of the spontaneous Raman signal.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy can also be used to observe other low frequency excitations of a solid, such as plasmons, magnons, and superconducting gap excitations.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Distributed temperature sensing (DTS) uses the Raman-shifted backscatter from laser pulses to determine the temperature along optical fibers.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The orientation of an anisotropic crystal can be found from the polarization of Raman-scattered light with respect to the crystal and the polarization of the laser light, if the crystal structure's point group is known.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In nanotechnology, a Raman microscope can be used to analyze nanowires to better understand their structures, and the radial breathing mode of carbon nanotubes is commonly used to evaluate their diameter.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman active fibers, such as aramid and carbon, have vibrational modes that show a shift in Raman frequency with applied stress.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Polypropylene fibers exhibit similar shifts.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In solid state chemistry and the bio-pharmaceutical industry, Raman spectroscopy can be used to not only identify active pharmaceutical ingredients (APIs), but to identify their polymorphic forms, if more than one exist.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For example, the drug Cayston (aztreonam), marketed by Gilead Sciences for cystic fibrosis, can be identified and characterized by IR and Raman spectroscopy.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Using the correct polymorphic form in bio-pharmaceutical formulations is critical, since different forms have different physical properties, like solubility and melting point.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy has a wide variety of applications in biology and medicine.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It has helped confirm the existence of low-frequency phonons in proteins and DNA, promoting studies of low-frequency collective motion in proteins and DNA and their biological functions.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman reporter molecules with olefin or alkyne moieties are being developed for tissue imaging with SERS-labeled antibodies.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy has also been used as a noninvasive technique for real-time, in situ biochemical characterization of wounds.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Multivariate analysis of Raman spectra has enabled development of a quantitative measure for wound healing progress.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Spatially offset Raman spectroscopy (SORS), which is less sensitive to surface layers than conventional Raman, can be used to discover counterfeit drugs without opening their packaging, and to non-invasively study biological tissue.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] A reason why Raman spectroscopy is useful in biological applications is because its results often do not face interference from water molecules, due to the fact that they have permanent dipole moments, and as a result, the Raman scattering cannot be picked up on.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This is a large advantage, specifically in biological applications.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy also has a wide usage for studying biominerals.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Lastly, Raman gas analyzers have many practical applications, including real-time monitoring of anesthetic and respiratory gas mixtures during surgery.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy has been used in several research projects as a means to detect explosives from a safe distance using laser beams.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy is being further developed so it could be used in the clinical setting.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman4Clinic is a European organization that is working on incorporating Raman Spectroscopy techniques in the medical field.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] They are currently working on different projects, one of them being monitoring cancer using bodily fluids such as urine and blood samples which are easily accessible.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This technique would be less stressful on the patients than constantly having to take biopsies which are not always risk free.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In photovoltaics, Raman spectroscopy has gained more interest in the past few years demonstrating high efficacy in delivering important properties for such materials.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This includes optoelectronic and physicochemical properties such as open circuit voltage, efficiency, and crystalline structure.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This has been demonstrated with several photovoltaic technologies, including kesterite-based, CIGS devices, Monocrystalline silicon cells, and perovskites devices.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy is an efficient and non-destructive way to investigate works of art and cultural heritage artifacts, in part because it is a non-invasive process which can be applied *in situ*.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It can be used to analyze the corrosion products on the surfaces of artifacts (statues, pottery, etc.), which can lend insight into the corrosive environments experienced by the artifacts.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The resulting spectra can also be compared to the spectra of surfaces that are cleaned or intentionally corroded, which can aid in determining the authenticity of valuable historical artifacts.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It is capable of identifying individual pigments in paintings and their degradation products, which can provide insight into the working method of an artist in addition to aiding in authentication of paintings.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It also gives information about the original state of the painting in cases where the pigments have degraded with age.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In addition to paintings and artifacts, Raman spectroscopy can be used to investigate the chemical composition of historical documents (such as the Book of Kells), which can provide insight about the social and economic conditions when they were created.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It also offers a noninvasive way to determine the best method of preservation or conservation of such cultural heritage artifacts, by providing insight into the causes behind deterioration.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The IRUG (Infrared and Raman Users Group) Spectral Database is a rigorously peer-reviewed online database of IR and Raman reference spectra for cultural heritage materials such as works of art, architecture, and archaeological artifacts.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The database is open for the general public to peruse, and includes interactive spectra for over a hundred different types of pigments and paints.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectroscopy offers several advantages for microscopic analysis.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Since it is a light scattering technique, specimens do not need to be fixed or sectioned.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman spectra can be collected from a very small volume (< 1 μm in diameter, < 10 μm in depth); these spectra allow the identification of species present in that volume.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Water does not generally interfere with Raman spectral analysis.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Thus, Raman spectroscopy is suitable for the microscopic examination of minerals, materials such as polymers and ceramics, cells, proteins and forensic trace evidence.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] A Raman microscope begins with a standard optical microscope, and adds an excitation laser, a monochromator or polychromator, and a sensitive detector (such as a charge-coupled device (CCD), or photomultiplier tube (PMT)).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] FT-Raman has also been used with microscopes, typically in combination with near-infrared (NIR) laser excitation.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Ultraviolet microscopes and UV enhanced optics must be used when a UV laser source is used for Raman microspectroscopy.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In *direct imaging* (also termed *global imaging* or *wide-field illumination*), the whole field of view is examined for light scattering integrated over a small range of wavenumbers (Raman shifts).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For instance, a wavenumber characteristic for cholesterol could be used to record the distribution of cholesterol within a cell culture.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This technique is being used for the characterization of large-scale devices, mapping of different compounds and dynamics study.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] It has already been used for the characterization of graphene layers, J-aggregated dyes inside carbon nanotubes and multiple other 2D materials such as MoS2 and WSe2.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Since the excitation beam is dispersed over the whole field of view, those measurements can be done without damaging the sample.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The most common approach is *hyperspectral imaging* or *chemical imaging*, in which thousands of Raman spectra are acquired from all over the field of view by, for example, raster scanning of a focused laser beam through a sample.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The data can be used to generate images showing the location and amount of different components.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Having the full spectroscopic information available in every measurement spot has the advantage that several components can be mapped at the same time, including chemically similar and even polymorphic forms, which cannot be distinguished by detecting only one single wavenumber.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Furthermore, material properties such as stress and strain, crystal orientation, crystallinity and incorporation of foreign ions into crystal lattices (e.g., doping, solid solution series) can be determined from hyperspectral maps.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Taking the cell culture example, a hyperspectral image could show the distribution of cholesterol, as well as proteins, nucleic acids, and fatty acids.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Sophisticated signal- and image-processing techniques can be used to ignore the presence of water, culture media, buffers, and other interferences.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Because a Raman microscope is a diffraction-limited system, its spatial resolution depends on the wavelength of light, the numerical aperture of the focusing element, and — in the case of confocal microscopy — on the diameter of the confocal aperture.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] When operated in the visible to near-infrared range, a Raman microscope can achieve lateral resolutions of approx.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] 1 μm down to 250 nm, depending on the wavelength and type of objective lens (e.g., air *vs.* water or oil immersion lenses).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The depth resolution (if not limited by the optical penetration depth of the sample) can range from 1–6 μm with the smallest confocal pinhole aperture to tens of micrometers when operated without a confocal pinhole.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Depending on the sample, the high laser power density due to microscopic focussing can have the benefit of enhanced photobleaching of molecules emitting interfering fluorescence.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] However, the laser wavelength and laser power have to be carefully selected for each type of sample to avoid its degradation.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Applications of Raman imaging range from materials sciences to biological studies.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For each type of sample, the measurement parameters have to be individually optimized.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For that reason, modern Raman microscopes are often equipped with several lasers offering different wavelengths, a set of objective lenses, and neutral density filters for tuning of the laser power reaching the sample.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Selection of the laser wavelength mainly depends on optical properties of the sample and on the aim of the investigation.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For example, Raman microscopy of biological and medical specimens is often performed using red to near-infrared excitation (e.g., 785 nm, or 1,064 nm wavelength).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Due to typically low absorbances of biological samples in this spectral range, the risk of damaging the specimen as well as autofluorescence emission are reduced, and high penetration depths into tissues can be achieved.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] However, the intensity of Raman scattering at long wavelengths is low (owing to the ω4 dependence of Raman scattering intensity), leading to long acquisition times.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] On the other hand, resonance Raman imaging of single-cell algae at 532 nm (green) can specifically probe the carotenoid distribution within a cell by a using low laser power of ~5 μW and only 100 ms acquisition time.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman scattering, specifically tip-enhanced Raman spectroscopy, produces high resolution hyperspectral images of single molecules, atoms, and DNA.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman scattering is polarization sensitive and can provide detailed information on symmetry of Raman active modes.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] While conventional Raman spectroscopy identifies chemical composition, polarization effects on Raman spectra can reveal information on the orientation of molecules in single crystals and anisotropic materials, e.g. strained plastic sheets, as well as the symmetry of vibrational modes.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Polarization–dependent Raman spectroscopy uses (plane) polarized laser excitation from a polarizer.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The Raman scattered light collected is passed through a second polarizer (called the analyzer) before entering the detector.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The analyzer is oriented either parallel or perpendicular to the polarization of the laser.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Spectra acquired with the analyzer set at both perpendicular and parallel to the excitation plane can be used to calculate the depolarization ratio.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Typically a polarization scrambler is placed between the analyzer and detector also.It is convenient in polarized Raman spectroscopy to describe the propagation and polarization directions using Porto's notation, described by and named after Brazilian physicist Sergio Pereira da Silva Porto.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] For isotropic solutions, the Raman scattering from each mode either retains the polarization of the laser or becomes partly or fully depolarized.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] If the vibrational mode involved in the Raman scattering process is totally symmetric then the polarization of the Raman scattering will be the same as that of the incoming laser beam.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In the case that the vibrational mode is not totally symmetric then the polarization will be lost (scrambled) partially or totally, which is referred to as depolarization.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Hence polarized Raman spectroscopy can provide detailed information as to the symmetry labels of vibrational modes.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] In the solid state, polarized Raman spectroscopy can be useful in the study of oriented samples such as single crystals.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The polarizability of a vibrational mode is not equal along and across the bond.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Therefore, the intensity of the Raman scattering will be different when the laser's polarization is along and orthogonal to a particular bond axis.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This effect can provide information on the orientation of molecules with a single crystal or material.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The spectral information arising from this analysis is often used to understand macro-molecular orientation in crystal lattices, liquid crystals or polymer samples.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The polarization technique is useful in understanding the connections between molecular symmetry, Raman activity, and peaks in the corresponding Raman spectra.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Polarized light in one direction only gives access to some Raman–active modes, but rotating the polarization gives access to other modes.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Each mode is separated according to its symmetry.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] When polarized light interacts with a molecule, it distorts the molecule which induces an equal and opposite effect in the plane-wave, causing it to be rotated by the difference between the orientation of the molecule and the angle of polarization of the light wave.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] If ${\textstyle \rho \geq {\frac {3}{4}}}$ , then the vibrations at that frequency are *depolarized*; meaning they are not totally symmetric.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Resonance Raman selection rules can be explained by the Kramers–Heisenberg equation using the Albrecht A and B terms, as demonstrated.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The polarizability operator connecting the initial and final states expresses the transition polarizability as a matrix element, as a function of the incidence frequency ω0.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The directions x, y, and z in the molecular frame are represented by the Cartesian tensor ρ and σ here.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Analyzing Raman excitation patterns requires the use of this equation, which is a sum-over-states expression for polarizability.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This series of profiles illustrates the connection between a Raman active vibration's excitation frequency and intensity.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] This method takes into account sums over Franck-Condon's active vibrational states and provides insight into electronic absorption and emission spectra.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Nevertheless, the work highlights a flaw in the sum-over-states method, especially for large molecules like visible chromophores, which are commonly studied in Raman spectroscopy.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The difficulty arises from the potentially infinite number of intermediary steps needed.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] While lowering the sum at higher vibrational states can help tiny molecules get over this issue, larger molecules find it more challenging when there are more terms in the sum, particularly in the condensed phase when individual eigenstates cannot be resolved spectrally.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] To overcome this, two substitute techniques that do not require adding eigenstates can be considered.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Among these two methods are available: the transform method. and Heller's time-dependent approach.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The goal of both approaches is to take into consideration the frequency-dependent Raman cross-section σR(ω0) of a particular normal mode.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] At least 25 variations of Raman spectroscopy have been developed.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The usual purpose is to enhance the sensitivity (e.g., Surface-enhanced Raman spectroscopy (SERS)), to improve the spatial resolution (Raman microscopy), or to acquire very specific information (resonance Raman).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Terms such as *spontaneous Raman spectroscopy* or *normal Raman spectroscopy* summarize Raman spectroscopy techniques based on Raman scattering by using normal far-field optics as described above.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Variants of normal Raman spectroscopy exist with respect to excitation-detection geometries, combination with other techniques, use of special (polarizing) optics and specific choice of excitation wavelengths for resonance enhancement.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Enhancement of Raman scattering is achieved by local electric-field enhancement by optical near-field effects (e.g. localized surface plasmons).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Raman signal enhancements are achieved through non-linear optical effects, typically realized by mixing two or more wavelengths emitted by spatially and temporally synchronized pulsed lasers.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Morphologically Directed Raman Spectroscopy (MDRS) combines automated particle imaging and Raman microspectroscopy into a singular integrated platform in order to provide particle size, shape, and chemical identification.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Automated particle imaging determines the particle size and shape distributions of components within a blended sample from images of individual particles.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The information gathered from automated particle imaging is then utilized to direct the Raman spectroscopic analysis.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] The Raman spectroscopic analytical process is performed on a randomly selected subset of the particles, allowing chemical identification of the sample's multiple components.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p01] Tens of thousands of particles can be imaged in a matter of minutes using the MDRS method, making the process ideal for forensic analysis and investigating counterfeit pharmaceuticals and subsequent adjudications.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] Where, $\alpha$ is the 3x3 polarizability tensor.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] In the **double-harmonic approximations**, the potential energy is expanded to the **second order** near equilibrium (harmonic force fields), while polarizability, is truncated at **first order** in the normal coordinates.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] In practice, $\alpha$ can be calculated through analytical methods or by employing the finite difference method for energy under small perturbations in $\mathbf {F}$ .
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] Where M is the diagonal matrix of atomic masses and L is the matrix of orthonormal eigenvectors (normal modes).
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] Since the $\partial {\boldsymbol {\alpha }}/\partial \mathbf {R}$ is known from finite differences or gradient calculation, it will used to calculate $Q_{p}$ , and further to get the Raman activities.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] Since some thermodynamic calculations ignored in the harmonic approximation, DFT-calculated harmonic frequencies are systematically **too high**.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] For example, the B3LYP/TZVP scaling factor is 0.965.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] Before to calculating the static spectrum, the structure must be optimized to its lowest energy point using the same or an approximate DFT basis set/functional.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] The mentioned static (harmonic) method also has been integrated into the Gaussian software as default, using the keyword Opt Freq=Raman to calculate.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] The harmonic approximation methods ignore some non-harmonic calculations.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] As an alternative, *ab initio* or machine-learned molecular-dynamics trajectories provide dynamic Raman spectrum.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] At each time step, the real-time polarizability tensor ${\boldsymbol {\alpha }}(t)$ is calculated, from the isotropic and anisotropic components we mentioned as $\alpha _{\mathrm {iso} }(t)$ and $\alpha _{\mathrm {aniso} }(t)$ , there will obtained from dynamical trajectory.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] This expression is derived from the angular momentum averaging of scattered lights from the random molecular orientations.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] The factor 4/3 the iso/aniso probably contribution.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] The ratio show the information on the symmetry of the vibrational modes.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] So, from the time dependent polarizability tensor ${\boldsymbol {\alpha }}(t)$ , the isotropic and anisotropic time series can be obtained.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] Their autocorrelation functions are calculated, Fourier transformed, and finally combined using the rotational averaging method to generate the total Raman spectrum.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] This polarizability-autocorrelation Fourier transform method naturally integrates anharmonic coupling, temperature broadening, and the polarization effects.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] It is providing a realistic description of Raman spectroscopy beyond the harmonic approximation.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] In recent years, machine learning has become a powerful tool in Raman spectroscopy, enabling data-driven prediction and interpretation of spectral line characteristics.
[src:infrared-spectroscopy/raman-spectroscopy-p02] Such as machine learned interatomic potential and generative model.
